enames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ligne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from Linne (Lower Saxony), or North German topographic name equivalent to   Linde   1 ‘lime tree’.","Swedish (<b>Linné</b>): topographic or ornamental name derived from <i>lind</i> ‘linden tree, lime tree’, a cognate of 1 above. The original humanistic form of the surname, <b>Linnæus</b>, is still found in Sweden.","History: The most famous bearer of the Swedish surname <i>Linné</i> was botanist Carl von Linné (1707–78), born <i>Linnæus</i>. The surname <i>Linnæus</i> was adopted by Carl's father Nils Ingemarsson after a giant linden tree that grew on his homestead."],"variants":[{"name":"Linde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Nels, Gunner, Lars.  German Kurt, Dieter, Erna, Fritz, Hasso, Markus, Otto, Ralf.","German, Dutch, and Scandinavian: topographic name for someone who lived by a conspicuous lime tree, Middle High German, Dutch <i>linde</i>, Scandinavian <i>lind</i>. There are several places, especially in northern Germany, named with this word, and the name may be a habitational name from any of these. The word was also used in a number of Old High German women's personal names, with the meaning ‘shield’ or ‘spear’ (these being made from the hard wood of the lime); it is possible that the surname in some cases is from a short form of one of these. As a Swedish name it is often ornamental rather than topographic. Compare   Lindy  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German <i>Linde</i> ‘lime tree’ (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Thierry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Germanic <i>Theodoric</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people’ and ‘rule’.  Compare  <b>Terry</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thierry II de Ligne was born in 1130, his father, Seigneur Thierry I de Ligne, was 26 and his mother, Marguerite de Fontaines, was 31. He married Elisabeth d'Antoing in 1150. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1190, at the age of 60, and was buried in Cambron, Aisne, Picardie, France."},"et":{"1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1172":"1140–1172","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1105–1176":"1105–1176","1100–1144":"1100–1144","1190":"1190","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1172":"1172","11 mai 1144":"11. mai 1144","1180":"1180","1105":"1105","1246":"1246","1145":"1145","1144":"1144","1100":"1100","Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgium":"Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgia","Cambron":"Cambron, Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgique":"Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgia"},"fi":{"1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1172":"1140–1172","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1105–1176":"1105–1176","1100–1144":"1100–1144","1190":"1190","about 1180":"noin 1180","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1172":"1172","11 mai 1144":"11. toukokuuta 1144","1180":"1180","1105":"1105","1246":"1246","1145":"1145","1144":"1144","1100":"1100","Ligne, Ath, Ha